> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PCAML507 - INTERNET OF THINGS LAB
> - **Module:** Module Experiment 2
> - **Topic:** Configure the IoT Trainer kit to send sensor data to a local server for storage and visualization. Use basic analytics to process the data.

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

**Internet of Things (IoT) Trainer Kit** is a compact, integrated development platform comprising one or more **microcontroller units (MCUs)** (e.g., ESP32, ESP8266, Arduino Uno + Wi-Fi shield, Raspberry Pi Pico W), a set of **on-board sensors** (temperature, humidity, light, gas, PIR, etc.), **actuators**, and **wireless communication modules**, designed to provide a hands-on, plug-and-play environment for prototyping **sensor-to-cloud** and **sensor-to-server** data pipelines.

In the context of the KTU 2024 Scheme Experiment 2, the trainer kit is configured to:
1. **Read** environmental/process data from sensors (analog/digital).
2. **Publish** this data over a local network (LAN) to a **local server** (running on a host PC or Raspberry Pi) using lightweight IoT protocols such as **MQTT** (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport) or **HTTP/REST**.
3. **Store** the incoming telemetry in a time-series database (e.g., **InfluxDB**) or relational store (**MySQL/SQLite**).
4. **Visualize** the data through a dashboard (e.g., **Node-RED Dashboard**, **Grafana**, or **ThingsBoard**).
5. **Analyze** the data using basic statistical techniques — thresholding, moving averages, min/max/mean, and simple anomaly flagging.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Syllabus Highlight (PCAML507 – Module 2):** This experiment directly addresses **CO2 – "Configure IoT devices to communicate with local/edge servers and apply basic data analytics on the acquired sensor data."** The examiner expects students to demonstrate the *complete data path* — from sensor pin to dashboard pixel.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — "The Post Office of Tiny Devices"

Imagine every sensor in the IoT trainer kit is a **citizen living in a small village** (the microcontroller). This citizen regularly measures something useful — say, the room temperature. Now, the citizen wants to share this measurement with a **town hall** (the local server), where the mayor (a database) records it and the town crier (a dashboard) announces it on a public board.

But the citizen cannot just *shout* across the village — there is too much noise, and the mayor would miss messages. So the citizen **writes the reading on a postcard**, **addresses it with a topic** (e.g., `"home/livingroom/temp"`), and **hands it to a postman** (the **MQTT broker** running on the local server). The postman delivers the postcard to:
- The **archive room** (database) — for permanent storage.
- The **public board** (dashboard) — for visualization.
- The **analyst desk** (analytics engine) — for processing.

The post office (broker) is the **central nervous system** of the entire pipeline. This postcard-delivery model is exactly how **MQTT** — the de-facto IoT protocol — works.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Terminology (Board-Exam Vocabulary):**
> - **Publisher:** The sensor node (trainer kit) that emits data.
> - **Subscriber:** The dashboard, database, or analytics module that receives data.
> - **Broker:** The MQTT server (e.g., **Mosquitto**) that routes messages.
> - **Topic:** A hierarchical address string (e.g., `iot/lab/sensor1/temperature`).
> - **Telemetry:** The sensor measurement payload sent over the network.

## 1.3 Physical Constants and Standard Metrics (Bold Emphasis)

The following standard engineering metrics are commonly evaluated in KTU viva and lab records:

- **Default MQTT Port:** **1883** (plain TCP) / **8883** (TLS-encrypted).
- **Default HTTP Port for REST APIs:** **80** (or **5000**, **8080** for dev servers).
- **Wi-Fi Frequency Band (IoT kits):** **2.4 GHz** (IEEE 802.11 b/g/n).
- **Typical Sensor Sampling Rate:** **1 Hz to 10 Hz** (1–10 samples/second).
- **MQTT QoS Levels:** **0** (at most once), **1** (at least once), **2** (exactly once).
- **ESP32 Operating Voltage:** **3.3 V** (logic level); onboard sensors typically use **3.3 V** or **5 V** rails.
- **ADC Resolution (ESP32):** **12-bit** → **4096 discrete levels** (0 to 4095).

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Layered Architecture of the Sensor-to-Dashboard Pipeline

The complete data path can be decomposed into **five functional layers**, mapped directly to the **5-layer IoT Reference Model (Perera et al., 2014)** adopted in the KTU 2024 syllabus:

### Layer 1 — **Perception / Sensor Layer**
- Physical sensors transduce environmental phenomena (heat, light, motion) into electrical signals.
- **Examples on the trainer kit:** DHT11/DHT22 (temperature + humidity), LDR (light), MQ-2 (gas), PIR (motion), BMP280 (pressure).
- Output: Analog voltage (0–3.3 V) or digital bitstream (e.g., I²C, SPI, 1-Wire).

### Layer 2 — **Network / Communication Layer**
- The MCU packages the sensor reading into a structured **payload** (commonly **JSON** for HTTP, or a **byte array** for MQTT).
- Transmission occurs over **Wi-Fi** (IEEE 802.11), using **TCP/IP** as the transport.
- Protocol choice:
  - **MQTT** → lightweight, publish/subscribe, ideal for low-bandwidth, high-latency LANs.
  - **HTTP/REST** → request/response, easier to debug, but heavier headers.
  - **CoAP** → constrained environments, UDP-based.

### Layer 3 — **Middleware / Broker Layer**
- The **MQTT broker** (e.g., **Eclipse Mosquitto**, **EMQ X**, **HiveMQ**) accepts incoming messages, filters them by **topic**, and dispatches them to all matching subscribers.
- Operates on the local server (host PC's `localhost` or a Raspberry Pi on the same LAN).
- IP discovery: The trainer kit connects to the broker's **IP address** (e.g., `192.168.1.10`) over **port 1883**.

### Layer 4 — **Application / Analytics Layer**
- A subscriber service (e.g., **Node-RED**, **Python script**, **ThingsBoard rule chain**) ingests the messages and:
  1. **Parses** the JSON payload.
  2. **Stores** it in a database.
  3. **Computes** basic analytics (mean, threshold checks, rate of change).
  4. **Triggers actions** (e.g., turn on a buzzer if temperature > 40 °C).

### Layer 5 — **Presentation / Visualization Layer**
- A web-based dashboard renders the data in real time as **line graphs**, **gauges**, **bar charts**, and **status indicators**.
- Tools: **Grafana** (with InfluxDB), **Node-RED Dashboard**, **ThingsBoard Web UI**, **Plotly Dash**.

## 2.2 The MQTT Protocol — Why It Wins for IoT

MQTT follows a **publish/subscribe** paradigm, decoupling the producer (sensor) from the consumer (dashboard). This is fundamentally different from HTTP's request/response model.

### Operational Flow:
1. The sensor (client) opens a **TCP connection** to the broker on **port 1883**.
2. It sends a **CONNECT** packet containing `clientID`, `username`, `password`, `keepAlive`, and `cleanSession` flags.
3. The broker responds with a **CONNACK** (Connection Acknowledgement).
4. The client sends a **PUBLISH** packet with a topic (e.g., `iot/lab/temp`) and a payload (e.g., `{"value": 28.4, "unit": "C"}`).
5. The broker forwards the packet to all clients that have **subscribed** to that topic (or topic wildcard).

### Topic Wildcards (Examiner's Favorite):
- `+` → single-level wildcard, e.g., `iot/lab/+/temp` matches `iot/lab/sensor1/temp` and `iot/lab/sensor2/temp`.
- `#` → multi-level wildcard, e.g., `iot/lab/#` matches everything under `iot/lab/`.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| **Concept** | **Formula / Standard Value** | **Description** | **Unit** |
|---|---|---|---|
| ADC to Voltage | $V = \frac{ADC\_value}{2^{n} - 1} \times V_{ref}$ | Converts raw 12-bit ADC reading to actual voltage | Volts (V) |
| DHT11 Temperature Range | $-0$ to $\mathbf{+50}$ | Standard DHT11 measurable range | °C |
| DHT11 Accuracy | $\pm \mathbf{2}$ | Typical sensor tolerance | °C |
| MQTT Keep-Alive | $t_{ka}$ | Heartbeat interval to maintain connection | seconds |
| Throughput (MQTT) | $T = \frac{P \times N}{t}$ | $P$ = payload bytes, $N$ = msgs/sec, $t$ = time | bytes/sec |
| Moving Average | $\bar{x}_{n} = \alpha \cdot x_{n} + (1 - \alpha) \cdot \bar{x}_{n-1}$ | Exponentially weighted smoothing, $0 < \alpha \le 1$ | dimensionless |
| Threshold Condition | $x > x_{th} \Rightarrow$ Alert | Basic analytics trigger | — |
| Standard MQTT Port | $\mathbf{1883}$ | Default unencrypted MQTT port | TCP port |
| ESP32 Wi-Fi Tx Power | $\mathbf{0}$ to $\mathbf{+20}$ | Configurable transmission power | dBm |
| Sample Rate (Nyquist) | $f_s \ge 2 \cdot f_{max}$ | Minimum sampling to avoid aliasing | Hz |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Exam Tip:** The **moving average (EMA)** formula is the *single most tested analytics expression* in the IoT lab exam. Memorize it and be ready to substitute numerical values.

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

This sensor-to-server pipeline is the foundational building block of:
- **Smart agriculture** — soil moisture and climate data sent to a local farm server.
- **Industrial SCADA** — machine vibration and temperature to a plant-floor historian.
- **Smart classrooms / hostels** — air-quality and occupancy monitoring on campus LANs.
- **Healthcare wearables** — patient vitals to a bedside Raspberry Pi gateway.
- **Environmental monitoring** — weather stations in remote field deployments.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why a *local* server (and not the cloud)?** For KTU lab evaluations, a local server is preferred because (a) it does not require internet access during the exam, (b) it gives full control over the data, and (c) it teaches the student the entire stack without abstraction by third-party IoT clouds.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Procedure, Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Hardware & Software Inventory (Pre-Experiment Setup)

### Hardware:
- IoT Trainer Kit (ESP32 / NodeMCU / Arduino + ESP-01 shield).
- Sensors: **DHT11** (temp + humidity), **LDR** (light), **MQ-2** (gas), **PIR** (motion).
- USB cable, jumper wires, host PC or Raspberry Pi.
- Wi-Fi router (2.4 GHz) for the local LAN.

### Software Stack (Local Server Side):
- **MQTT Broker:** Eclipse Mosquitto (`mosquitto` package).
- **Visualization & Rule Engine:** Node-RED (with `node-red-dashboard`).
- **Database (optional):** InfluxDB + Grafana, *or* SQLite via Node-RED.
- **Python 3.x** (for analytics scripts).
- Arduino IDE / PlatformIO (for trainer kit firmware).

## 3.2 Step-by-Step Procedure (The KTU Lab Record Format)

### **Step 1 — Network Preparation**
- Connect the host PC and the trainer kit to the **same Wi-Fi network** (e.g., SSID `KTU_LAB`).
- Find the host PC's IP address:
  - Windows: `ipconfig` → look for `IPv4 Address` (e.g., `192.168.1.10`).
  - Linux/Mac: `ifconfig` or `ip a`.

### **Step 2 — Install and Start the MQTT Broker**
On the host PC (Linux example):

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install mosquitto mosquitto-clients -y
sudo systemctl start mosquitto
sudo systemctl enable mosquitto
```

Verify the broker is listening:

```bash
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep 1883
```

> [!NOTE]
> Expected output should show `0.0.0.0:1883` — meaning the broker is accepting connections on all interfaces.

### **Step 3 — Install Node-RED and Dashboard**

```bash
bash <(curl -sL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/node-red/linux-installers/master/deb/update-nodejs-and-nodered)
sudo systemctl start nodered
```

Open the Node-RED editor at `http://localhost:1880` and install the dashboard palette:

```bash
cd ~/.node-red
npm install node-red-dashboard
```

Restart Node-RED after installation.

### **Step 4 — Firmware: Program the Trainer Kit (ESP32 + DHT11 + LDR)**

Below is the **complete Arduino sketch** (model answer code) for the trainer kit.

```cpp
// ============================================================
//  KTU PCAML507 — Module 2 Experiment
//  IoT Trainer Kit (ESP32) → Local MQTT Broker
//  Sensors: DHT11 (Temp+Hum), LDR (Light), MQ-2 (Gas)
// ============================================================
#include <WiFi.h>
#include <PubSubClient.h>
#include <DHT.h>

// ---- Wi-Fi Credentials ----
const char* ssid     = "KTU_LAB";
const char* password = "lab123456";

// ---- MQTT Broker (Local Server) ----
const char* mqtt_server = "192.168.1.10";   // Host PC IP
const int   mqtt_port   = 1883;
const char* mqtt_topic  = "iot/lab/sensor1/data";

// ---- Sensor Pin Definitions ----
#define DHTPIN   4        // GPIO4 for DHT11 DATA
#define DHTTYPE  DHT11
#define LDR_PIN  34       // GPIO34 (ADC1_CH6) for LDR
#define MQ2_PIN  35       // GPIO35 (ADC1_CH7) for MQ-2

DHT dht(DHTPIN, DHTTYPE);
WiFiClient espClient;
PubSubClient client(espClient);

unsigned long lastMsg = 0;
const long interval = 3000;   // 3-second publish interval

void setup_wifi() {
  delay(10);
  Serial.println("Connecting to Wi-Fi...");
  WiFi.begin(ssid, password);
  while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED) {
    delay(500);
    Serial.print(".");
  }
  Serial.println();
  Serial.print("Wi-Fi connected, IP: ");
  Serial.println(WiFi.localIP());
}

void callback(char* topic, byte* payload, unsigned int length) {
  // Handle incoming messages (e.g., actuator commands)
  Serial.print("Message arrived on topic: ");
  Serial.println(topic);
}

void reconnect() {
  while (!client.connected()) {
    Serial.print("Attempting MQTT connection...");
    String clientId = "ESP32-";
    clientId += String(random(0xffff), HEX);
    if (client.connect(clientId.c_str())) {
      Serial.println("connected");
      client.subscribe("iot/lab/cmd");   // Subscribe to command topic
    } else {
      Serial.print("failed, rc=");
      Serial.print(client.state());
      delay(2000);
    }
  }
}

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  dht.begin();
  setup_wifi();
  client.setServer(mqtt_server, mqtt_port);
  client.setCallback(callback);
}

void loop() {
  if (!client.connected()) reconnect();
  client.loop();

  unsigned long now = millis();
  if (now - lastMsg > interval) {
    lastMsg = now;

    // ---- Read Sensors ----
    float temperature = dht.readTemperature();   // °C
    float humidity    = dht.readHumidity();      // %
    int   ldrRaw      = analogRead(LDR_PIN);     // 0-4095
    int   mq2Raw      = analogRead(MQ2_PIN);     // 0-4095

    // ---- Convert LDR ADC to approximate lux ----
    // Vout = (ADC / 4095) * 3.3V
    float ldrVoltage = (ldrRaw / 4095.0) * 3.3;
    // Empirical linear approximation (calibration-dependent)
    int   lightPct    = map(ldrRaw, 0, 4095, 0, 100);

    // ---- Construct JSON Payload ----
    char payload[256];
    snprintf(payload, sizeof(payload),
      "{\"temp\":%.1f,\"hum\":%.1f,\"light\":%d,\"gas\":%d,\"ts\":%lu}",
      temperature, humidity, lightPct, mq2Raw, millis());

    Serial.print("Publishing: ");
    Serial.println(payload);

    // ---- Publish to MQTT Broker ----
    client.publish(mqtt_topic, payload);
  }
}
```

**Code Walkthrough (Why each block exists):**

| **Block** | **Purpose** | **Why it matters for the exam** |
|---|---|---|
| `#include <PubSubClient.h>` | MQTT client library | Shows use of standardized IoT protocol |
| `client.setServer()` | Connect to broker | Demonstrates network configuration |
| `analogRead(LDR_PIN)` | Read 12-bit ADC | Tests ADC-to-voltage conversion knowledge |
| `snprintf(...)` | Build JSON payload | Shows structured data serialization |
| `client.publish()` | Send data to broker | Core publish/subscribe operation |

### **Step 5 — Node-RED Flow: Subscribe, Store, Visualize, Analyze**

In the Node-RED editor (`http://localhost:1880`), build the following flow:

#### Node 1 — **MQTT In**
- Server: `localhost:1883`
- Topic: `iot/lab/sensor1/data`
- QoS: `1`

#### Node 2 — **JSON Parse**
- Parses the incoming payload into a JS object.

#### Node 3 — **Function Node (Basic Analytics)**

```javascript
// ---- Basic Analytics Block ----
msg.payload.temp  = parseFloat(msg.payload.temp);
msg.payload.hum   = parseFloat(msg.payload.hum);
msg.payload.light = parseInt(msg.payload.light);
msg.payload.gas   = parseInt(msg.payload.gas);

// --- 1) Threshold alert ---
if (msg.payload.temp > 35.0) {
    msg.alert = "HIGH_TEMP";
    msg.alertColor = "red";
} else if (msg.payload.gas > 2000) {
    msg.alert = "GAS_DETECTED";
    msg.alertColor = "yellow";
} else {
    msg.alert = "NORMAL";
    msg.alertColor = "green";
}

// --- 2) Exponential Moving Average (EMA) ---
// alpha = 0.3 (smoothing factor)
const alpha = 0.3;
const ctx   = context.get('emaTemp') || 0;
const newEma = alpha * msg.payload.temp + (1 - alpha) * ctx;
context.set('emaTemp', newEma);
msg.payload.emaTemp = newEma;

// --- 3) Rate of change (°C per sample) ---
const prevTemp = context.get('prevTemp') || msg.payload.temp;
msg.payload.dT = msg.payload.temp - prevTemp;
context.set('prevTemp', msg.payload.temp);

return msg;
```

#### Node 4 — **MQTT Out (for analytics result re-publish)**
- Topic: `iot/lab/sensor1/analytics`

#### Node 5 — **Dashboard Widgets**
- **Gauge** → temperature (0–50 °C)
- **Gauge** → humidity (0–100 %)
- **Line chart** → time-series of temperature and EMA
- **Text** → alert status (color-coded)
- **Gauge** → gas level (0–4095 raw ADC)

## 3.3 Analytical Derivation — ADC to Physical Quantity

For the LDR sensor, the **raw 12-bit ADC value** must be converted to a meaningful engineering quantity. The derivation is shown in full KTU board-exam style:

$$V_{out} = \frac{ADC_{raw}}{2^{n} - 1} \times V_{ref}$$

**Step 1:** Identify the parameters from the ESP32 datasheet.

$$n = 12 \quad \text{(ADC resolution in bits)}$$

$$V_{ref} = 3.3 \text{ V} \quad \text{(default reference voltage)}$$

**Step 2:** Substitute into the formula for a sample reading of $ADC_{raw} = 2500$.

$$V_{out} = \frac{2500}{2^{12} - 1} \times 3.3$$

$$V_{out} = \frac{2500}{4095} \times 3.3$$

$$V_{out} = 0.6105 \times 3.3 = 2.0147 \text{ V}$$

**Step 3:** Convert voltage to a percentage of full scale (0–100%) for dashboard display.

$$\text{Light}_{pct} = \frac{V_{out}}{V_{ref}} \times 100 = \frac{2.0147}{3.3} \times 100 = 61.05\%$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Note:** The light percentage is a *linear* approximation. A real LDR-to-lux conversion requires a **logarithmic fit** because human eye perception and LDR resistance are non-linear. For lab purposes, the linear mapping is sufficient and is what the KTU examiner expects.

## 3.4 Exhaustive Validation Checklist

After running the experiment, verify each of the following:

1. ✅ MQTT broker is running (`sudo systemctl status mosquitto` shows `active (running)`).
2. ✅ Trainer kit's Serial Monitor shows `Wi-Fi connected` and `Publishing:` lines every **3 seconds**.
3. ✅ Node-RED **debug** node prints the incoming JSON payload.
4. ✅ Dashboard gauges update **in real time** (refresh < 1 second).
5. ✅ Analytics function correctly flags `HIGH_TEMP` when a heat source is applied near the DHT11.
6. ✅ EMA value smoothly tracks the raw temperature, lagging slightly — proving the smoothing is working.

