# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### **Q1. Define the MQTT protocol. List its three Quality of Service (QoS) levels with their delivery guarantees.** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024, Model]`

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

**MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport)** is a lightweight, publish/subscribe messaging protocol designed for low-bandwidth, high-latency, or unreliable networks. It operates over TCP/IP and follows a broker-mediated architecture where publishers and subscribers are decoupled through **topics**.

The three QoS levels are:

| **QoS Level** | **Name** | **Delivery Guarantee** |
|---|---|---|
| **QoS 0** | At most once | Fire-and-forget; no acknowledgement; possible loss |
| **QoS 1** | At least once | Acknowledged; possible duplicates |
| **QoS 2** | Exactly once | Four-way handshake; guaranteed single delivery |

---

### **Q2. Differentiate between the MQTT and HTTP protocols for IoT communication. State one scenario where each is preferred.** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Model]`

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| **Parameter** | **MQTT** | **HTTP** |
|---|---|---|
| Architecture | Publish/Subscribe | Request/Response |
| Header Size | **2 bytes** (fixed) | Hundreds of bytes (variable) |
| Transport | TCP (port 1883) | TCP (port 80) |
| Power Efficiency | High (low overhead) | Low (heavy headers) |
| Real-time Push | Native (broker forwards) | Requires polling or WebSocket |

**Preferred scenarios:**
- **MQTT** → Continuous sensor telemetry on a battery-powered node (e.g., remote weather station).
- **HTTP** → Infrequent configuration updates or firmware OTA (Over-The-Air) requests.

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks — Module Internal Choice)

### **Question A (14 Marks)**

#### **(a)** Explain the architecture of a local IoT data pipeline that connects an ESP32-based trainer kit to a dashboard via an MQTT broker. Include a labelled block diagram and describe the function of each layer. **(7 marks)** `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**Model Solution:**

The local IoT data pipeline consists of **five functional layers** as defined by the IoT reference architecture:

**1. Perception Layer (Sensors):**
The ESP32 trainer kit hosts sensors such as the **DHT11** (temperature/humidity), **LDR** (light), **MQ-2** (gas), and **PIR** (motion). These convert physical phenomena into electrical signals — analog voltages (0–3.3 V) for the LDR and MQ-2, and a digital 1-Wire protocol for the DHT11.

**2. Edge / Network Layer (ESP32 MCU):**
The ESP32 reads the sensors via its **12-bit ADC** (resolution = $2^{12} = 4096$ discrete levels). It packages the readings into a **JSON payload** such as:

```json
{"temp": 28.5, "hum": 65.0, "light": 70, "gas": 1200, "ts": 12345}
```

The payload is published via the **MQTT client** to the broker on the local server at IP `192.168.1.10` over **port 1883**.

**3. Middleware Layer (Mosquitto Broker):**
The **Eclipse Mosquitto** broker runs on the host PC (`localhost` or LAN IP). It accepts the published message on topic `iot/lab/sensor1/data` and **routes** it to all clients that have subscribed to that exact topic or a matching wildcard.

**4. Application Layer (Node-RED + Analytics):**
**Node-RED** subscribes to the MQTT topic, parses the JSON, and runs **basic analytics**:
- **Thresholding** — flags high temperature or gas leaks.
- **Exponential Moving Average (EMA)** — smooths noisy readings using the recurrence $\bar{x}_n = \alpha \cdot x_n + (1-\alpha) \cdot \bar{x}_{n-1}$ with $\alpha = 0.3$.
- **Rate of change** — computes $\Delta T = T_n - T_{n-1}$ to detect rapid environmental shifts.

**5. Presentation Layer (Dashboard):**
The processed data is rendered in a browser-based dashboard with **gauges** (for instantaneous values) and **line charts** (for time-series trends), updated in real time via **WebSocket** push from Node-RED.

**Block Diagram:** *(Refer to SECTION 4.1 for the full Mermaid diagram. Students should redraw a simplified version in the exam.)*

**Marks Distribution:** Layer-wise description — 1 mark each × 5 layers = 5 marks; Block diagram — 1 mark; Example payload/protocol — 1 mark = **Total 7 marks**.

