### **Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice**

#### **(a)** Describe the basic data analytics techniques that can be applied to IoT sensor streams. For each technique, give a one-line example using temperature data. **(7 marks)** `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Model Solution:**

Basic data analytics on IoT sensor streams can be classified into **four fundamental categories**:

**1. Descriptive Statistics:**
Compute summary measures to characterize the data distribution.
- *Example:* The mean temperature over the last hour is $28.3$ °C.
- *Formula:* $\bar{x} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} x_i$

**2. Threshold-Based Alerting:**
Compare each reading against a predefined boundary to trigger alerts.
- *Example:* If `temp > 35 °C`, sound a buzzer and display a red alert.
- *Logic:* $x_n > x_{th} \Rightarrow \text{Trigger Alert}$

**3. Smoothing / Filtering:**
Reduce sensor noise using a moving average or exponential filter.
- *Example:* The EMA of temperature with $\alpha = 0.3$ produces a smooth curve that filters out ±1 °C fluctuations.
- *Formula:* $\bar{x}_n = \alpha \cdot x_n + (1-\alpha) \cdot \bar{x}_{n-1}$

**4. Rate of Change / Trend Detection:**
Compute the difference between successive readings to detect rapid environmental changes.
- *Example:* If $\Delta T = T_n - T_{n-1} > 2$ °C per sample, flag as "rapid heating."
- *Logic:* $dT/dt \approx (T_n - T_{n-1}) / \Delta t$

**Marks Distribution:** Four techniques × 1.5 marks = 6 marks; Plus one bonus mark for the formula.

